04857nam a2200745Ia 9781501731013DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017310137 a10.7591/97815017310132doi  a(DE-B1597)503268  a(OCoLC)1082315649  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aB3181 7aPHI0160002bisacsh04a1932231 aStyfhals, Willem, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNo Spiritual Investment in the World :bGnosticism and Postwar German Philosophy /cWillem Styfhals. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©2019  a1 online resource (306 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSignale: Modern German Letters, Cultures, and Thought00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Crisis: Gnostic Dualism In Late Modernity -- t2. Eschaton: Gnostic Evil In History -- t3. Subversion: Heresy and Its Modern Afterlives -- t4. Nothingness: Dialectics of Religious Nihilism -- t5. Epoch: The Gnostic Age -- t6. Theodicy: Overcoming Gnosticism, Embracing the World -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThroughout the twentieth century, German writers, philosophers, theologians, and historians turned to Gnosticism to make sense of the modern condition. While some saw this ancient Christian heresy as a way to rethink modernity, most German intellectuals questioned Gnosticism's return in a contemporary setting. In No Spiritual Investment in the World, Willem Styfhals explores the Gnostic worldview's enigmatic place in these discourses on modernity, presenting a comprehensive intellectual history of Gnosticism's role in postwar German thought. Establishing the German-Jewish philosopher Jacob Taubes at the nexus of the debate, Styfhals traces how such figures as Hans Blumenberg, Hans Jonas, Eric Voegelin, Odo Marquard, and Gershom Scholem contended with Gnosticism and its tenets on evil and divine absence as metaphorical detours to address issues of cultural crisis, nihilism, and the legitimacy of the modern world. These concerns, he argues, centered on the difficulty of spiritual engagement in a world from which the divine has withdrawn. Reading Gnosticism against the backdrop of postwar German debates about secularization, political theology, and post-secularism, No Spiritual Investment in the World sheds new light on the historical contours of postwar German philosophy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aGerman Studies. 4aPhilosophy. 4aReligious Studies. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh  aJacob Taubes, Hans Blumenberg, Hans Jonas, Eric Voegelin, Odo Marquard, Gershom Scholem, secularization.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065198008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2019 Englishz978311061055008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2019z9783110606423oZDB-23-DPH40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501731013?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501731013423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501731013/original  a978-3-11-061055-0  EBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-061076-5  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishb2019  a978-3-11-065198-0  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTL